 Japan’: Shifting to Slow Tourism as a Rural Regeneration Tool in Japan -- t14. Tribe Tourism: A Case Study of the Tribewanted Project on Vorovoro, Fiji -- t15. Slow Tourism Initiatives: An Exploratory Study of Dutch Lifestyles Entrepreneurs in France -- t16. Slow Travel and Indian Culture: Philosophical and Practical Aspects -- t17. Reflecting Upon Slow Travel and Tourism Experiences0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing together scholars from the areas of tourism, leisure and cultural studies, eco-humanities and tourism management, this book examines the emerging phenomenon of slow tourism. The book explores the range of travel experiences that are part of growing consumer concerns with quality leisure time, environmental and cultural sustainability, as well as the embodied experience of place. Slow tourism encapsulates a range of lifestyle practices, mobilities and ethics that are connected to social movements such as slow food and cities, as well as specialist sectors such as ecotourism and voluntourism. The slow experience of temporality can evoke and incite different ways of being and moving, as well as different logics of desire that value travel experiences as forms of knowledge. Slow travel practices reflect a range of ethical-political positions that have yet to be critically explored in the academic literature despite the growth of industry discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aSocial movements. 0aTourismxPsychological aspects. 4aGEOGRAPHY. 4aSociology. 4aTourism industry. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Industries / Hospitality, Travel & Tourism.2bisacsh  aecotourism.  aenvironmental change.  ahedonism.  aslow food.  aslow mobilities.  aslow tourism initiatives.  aslow tourism.  aslow travel.  asust